.TH PAPER 1 "1 December 2013"
.SH NAME
.B paper
\- print paper configuration information
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBpaper\fR [\fB\-n\fR] [\fB\-s\fR] [\fB\-u\fR \fIUNIT\fR] [\fIPAPER\fR...|\fB\-a\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B paper
prints information about the given paper sizes, which can include the
standard form of its name, its width and height.
The name is matched case-insensitively, and ignoring spaces.
.PP
If neither a paper size nor the \fB\-a\fR option is given, the current
paper size is used.
.PP
The current paper size is obtained by looking in order at the following
values until a valid paper size is found:
.IP \[bu]
The \fBPAPERSIZE\fR environment variable
.IP \[bu]
The \fBLC_PAPER\fR environment variable (if supported by the system)
.IP \[bu]
The first paper size listed in the concatenation of
\fB~/.@PAPERSPECS@\fR (if it exists), or
\fB@sysconfdir@/@PAPERSPECS@\fR otherwise
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-a
Give information about all known paper sizes.
.TP
.B \-n
Print the name of paper. (By default, \fBpaper\fR does not print
the name of the paper when given exactly one paper size argument.)
.TP
.B \-s
Print the size (width followed by height) of the paper.
.TP
.B \-u " UNIT"
Specify the units in which to print dimensions.
See paperspecs(5) for a list of valid units.
By default, dimensions are printed in PostScript points.
.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.TP
.B PAPERSIZE
Paper size to use.
